# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dropwizard-java
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Dropwizard straddles the line between being a library and a framework.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Its goal is to provide performant, reliable implementations of everything a production-ready web application needs.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Because this functionality is extracted into a reusable library, your application remains lean and focused, reducing both time-to-market and maintenance burdens.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Because you can’t be a web application without HTTP, Dropwizard uses the Jetty HTTP library to embed an incredibly tuned HTTP server directly into your project.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Instead of handing your application off to a complicated application server, Dropwizard projects have a `main` method which spins up an HTTP server.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] For building RESTful web applications, we’ve found nothing beats Jersey (the JAX-RS reference implementation) in terms of features or performance.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] It allows you to write clean, testable classes which gracefully map HTTP requests to simple Java objects.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] It supports streaming output, matrix URI parameters, conditional `GET` requests, and much, much more.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] In terms of data formats, JSON has become the web’s *lingua franca*, and Jackson is the king of JSON on the JVM.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] In addition to being lightning fast, it has a sophisticated object mapper, allowing you to export your domain models directly.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] The Metrics library rounds things out, providing you with unparalleled insight into your code’s behavior in your production environment.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] In addition to Jetty, Jersey, and Jackson, Dropwizard also includes a number of libraries to help you ship more quickly and with fewer regrets.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Now that you’ve gotten the lay of the land, let’s dig in!
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] If you’re upgrading from an earlier version of Dropwizard, see the Upgrade Notes for Dropwizard 5.0.x for important information about the Java version requirement and other breaking changes.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] We recommend you use Maven for new Dropwizard applications.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] If you’re a big Ant / Ivy, Buildr, Gradle, SBT, Leiningen, or Gant fan, that’s cool, but we use Maven, and we’ll be using Maven as we go through this example application.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] If you have any questions about how Maven works, Maven: The Complete Reference should have what you’re looking for.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] We’ve got a Maven project set up now, and it’s time to start writing real code.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Each Dropwizard application has its own subclass of the `Configuration` class which specifies environment-specific parameters.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] These parameters are specified in a YAML configuration file which is deserialized to an instance of your application’s configuration class and validated.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] The application we’ll be building is a high-performance Hello World service, and one of our requirements is that we need to be able to vary how it says hello from environment to environment.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] We’ll need to specify at least two things to begin with: a template for saying hello and a default name to use in case the user doesn’t specify their name.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] There’s a lot going on here, so let’s unpack a bit of it.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] When this class is deserialized from the YAML file, it will pull two root-level fields from the YAML object: `template`, the template for our Hello World saying, and `defaultName`, the default name to use.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Both `template` and `defaultName` are annotated with `@NotEmpty`, so if the YAML configuration file has blank values for either or is missing `template` entirely an informative exception will be thrown, and your application won’t start.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Both the getters and setters for `template` and `defaultName` are annotated with `@JsonProperty`, which allows Jackson to both deserialize the properties from a YAML file but also to serialize it.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] The mapping from YAML to your application’s `Configuration` instance is done by Jackson.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] This means your `Configuration` class can use all of Jackson’s object-mapping annotations.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] The validation of `@NotEmpty` is handled by Hibernate Validator, which has a wide range of built-in constraints for you to use.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Dropwizard has *many* more configuration parameters than that, but they all have sane defaults so you can keep your configuration files small and focused.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] So save that YAML file in the directory you plan to run the fat jar from (see below) as `hello-world.yml`, because we’ll be getting up and running pretty soon, and we’ll need it.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Next up, we’re creating our application class!
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Combined with your project’s `Configuration` subclass, its `Application` subclass forms the core of your Dropwizard application.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] The `Application` class pulls together the various bundles and commands which provide basic functionality.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] As you can see, `HelloWorldApplication` is parameterized with the application’s configuration type, `HelloWorldConfiguration`.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] An `initialize` method is used to configure aspects of the application required before the application is run, like bundles, configuration source providers, etc.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Also, we’ve added a `static` `main` method, which will be our application’s entry point.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Right now, we don’t have any functionality implemented, so our `run` method is a little boring.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Before we can get into the nuts-and-bolts of our Hello World application, we need to stop and think about our API.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] The `id` field is a unique identifier for the saying, and `content` is the textual representation of the saying.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] This is a pretty simple POJO, but there are a few things worth noting here.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] This makes `Saying` instances *very* easy to reason about in multi-threaded environments as well as single-threaded environments.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Second, it uses the JavaBeans standard for the `id` and `content` properties.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] This allows Jackson to serialize it to the JSON we need.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] The Jackson object mapping code will populate the `id` field of the JSON object with the return value of `#getId()`, likewise with `content` and `#getContent()`.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] The JSON serialization here is done by Jackson, which supports far more than simple JavaBean objects like this one.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] In addition to the sophisticated set of annotations, you can even write your custom serializers and deserializers.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Now that we’ve got our representation class, it makes sense to start in on the resource it represents.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Jersey resources are the meat-and-potatoes of a Dropwizard application.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Each resource class is associated with a URI template.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Let’s start from the top and work our way down.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] `HelloWorldResource` has two annotations: `@Path` and `@Produces`.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] `@Path("/hello-world")` tells Jersey that this resource is accessible at the URI `/hello-world`, and `@Produces(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)` lets Jersey’s content negotiation code know that this resource produces representations which are `application/json`.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] `HelloWorldResource` takes two parameters for construction: the `template` it uses to produce the saying and the `defaultName` used when the user declines to tell us their name.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] An `AtomicLong` provides us with a cheap, thread-safe way of generating unique(ish) IDs.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Resource classes are used by multiple threads concurrently.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] In general, we recommend that resources be stateless/immutable, but it’s important to keep the context in mind.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] `#sayHello(Optional<String>)` is the meat of this class, and it’s a fairly simple method.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] The `@QueryParam("name")` annotation tells Jersey to map the `name` parameter from the query string to the `name` parameter in the method.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] If the client sends a request to `/hello-world?name=Dougie`, `sayHello` will be called with `Optional.of("Dougie")`; if there is no `name` parameter in the query string, `sayHello` will be called with `Optional.empty()`.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] If the client sends a request to `/hello-world?name=`, `sayHello` will be called with `Optional.of("")`.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] This may seem odd at first, but this follows the standards (an application may have different behavior depending on if a parameter is empty vs nonexistent).
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Inside the `sayHello` method, we increment the counter, format the template using `String.format(String, Object...)`, and return a new `Saying` instance.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Because `sayHello` is annotated with `@Timed`, Dropwizard automatically records the duration and rate of its invocations as a Metrics Timer.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Once `sayHello` has returned, Jersey takes the `Saying` instance and looks for a provider class which can write `Saying` instances as `application/json`.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Dropwizard has one such provider built in which allows for producing and consuming Java objects as JSON objects.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] The provider writes out the JSON and the client receives a `200 OK` response with a content type of `application/json`.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Before that will actually work, though, we need to go back to `HelloWorldApplication` and add this new resource class.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] When our application starts, we create a new instance of our resource class with the parameters from the configuration file and hand it off to the `Environment`, which acts like a registry of all the things your application can do.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] A Dropwizard application can contain *many* resource classes, each corresponding to its own URI pattern.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Just add another `@Path`-annotated resource class and call `register` with an instance of the new class.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Before we go too far, we should add a health check for our application.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Health checks give you a way of adding small tests to your application to allow you to verify that your application is functioning correctly in production.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] We **strongly** recommend that all of your applications have at least a minimal set of health checks.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] We recommend this so strongly, in fact, that Dropwizard will nag you should you neglect to add a health check to your project.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Since formatting strings is not likely to fail while an application is running (unlike, say, a database connection pool), we’ll have to get a little creative here.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] `TemplateHealthCheck` checks for two things: that the provided template is actually a well-formed format string, and that the template actually produces output with the given name.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] If the string is not a well-formed format string (for example, someone accidentally put `Hello, %s%` in the configuration file), then `String.format(String, Object...)` will throw an `IllegalFormatException` and the health check will implicitly fail.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] If the rendered saying doesn’t include the test string, the health check will explicitly fail by returning an unhealthy `Result`.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] We recommend that you build your Dropwizard applications as “fat” JAR files — single `.jar` files which contain *all* of the `.class` files required to run your application.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] This allows you to build a single deployable artifact which you can promote from your staging environment to your QA environment to your production environment without worrying about differences in installed libraries.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] To start building our Hello World application as a fat JAR, we need to configure a Maven plugin called `maven-shade`.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] If your application has a dependency which *must* be signed (e.g., a JCA/JCE provider or other trusted library), you have to add an exclusion to the `maven-shade-plugin` configuration for that library and include that JAR in the classpath.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Since Dropwizard is using the Java ServiceLoader functionality to register and load extensions, the minimizeJar option of the *maven-shade-plugin* will lead to non-working application JARs.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Dropwizard can also use the project version if it’s embedded in the JAR’s manifest as the `Implementation-Version`.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] This can be handy when trying to figure out what version of your application you have deployed on a machine.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Once you’ve got that configured, go into your project directory and run `mvn package` (or run the `package` goal from your IDE).
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Now that you’ve built a JAR file, it’s time to run it.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Dropwizard takes the first command line argument and dispatches it to a matching command.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] In this case, the only command available is `server`, which runs your application as an HTTP server.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Your Dropwizard application is now listening on ports `8080` for application requests and `8081` for administration requests.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] If you press `^C`, the application will shut down gracefully, first closing the server socket, then waiting for in-flight requests to be processed, then shutting down the process itself.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] However, while it’s up, let’s give it a whirl!
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] But that’s not all your application can do.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] One of the main reasons for using Dropwizard is the out-of-the-box operational tools it provides, all of which can be found on the admin port.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] If you click through to the metrics resource, you can see all of your application’s metrics represented as a JSON object.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] The threads resource allows you to quickly get a thread dump of all the threads running in that process.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] When a Jetty worker thread is handling an incoming HTTP request, the thread name is set to the method and URI of the request.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] This can be *very* helpful when debugging a poorly-behaving request.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] The healthcheck resource runs the health check class we wrote.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] `template` here is the result of your `TemplateHealthCheck`, which unsurprisingly passed.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] `deadlocks` is a built-in health check which looks for deadlocked JVM threads and prints out a listing if any are found.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] You’ve got a Hello World application ready for production (except for the lack of tests) that’s capable of doing 30,000-50,000 requests per second.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] Hopefully, you’ve gotten a feel for how Dropwizard combines Jetty, Jersey, Jackson, and other stable, mature libraries to provide a phenomenal platform for developing RESTful web applications.
[src:dropwizard-java/getting-started] There’s a lot more to Dropwizard than is covered here (commands, bundles, servlets, advanced configuration, validation, HTTP clients, database clients, views, etc.), all of which is covered by the User Manual.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Java gained popularity shortly after its release, and has been a popular programming language since then.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Java was the third most popular programming language in 2022 according to GitHub.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Although still widely popular, there has been a gradual decline in use of Java in recent years with other languages using JVM gaining popularity.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Java was designed by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] It was released in May 1995 as a core component of Sun's Java platform.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] The original and reference implementation Java compilers, virtual machines (VMs), and class libraries were released by Sun under proprietary licenses.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] As of May 2007, in compliance with the specifications of the Java Community Process, Sun had relicensed most of its Java technologies under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Oracle, which bought Sun in 2010, offers its own HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] However, the official reference implementation is the OpenJDK JVM, which is open-source software used by most developers and is the default JVM for almost all Linux distributions.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] As of March 2026, Java 26 is the current version.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] James Gosling, Mike Sheridan, and Patrick Naughton initiated the Java language project in June 1991.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Java was originally designed for interactive television, but it was too advanced for the digital cable television industry at the time.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] The language was initially called *Oak* after an oak tree that stood outside Gosling's office.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Later the project went by the name *Green* and was finally renamed *Java*, from Java coffee, a type of coffee from Indonesia.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Gosling designed Java with a C/C++-style syntax that system and application programmers would find familiar.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Sun Microsystems released the first public implementation as Java 1.0 in 1996.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] It promised write once, run anywhere (WORA) functionality, providing no-cost run-times on popular platforms.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Fairly secure and featuring configurable security, it allowed network- and file-access restrictions.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Major web browsers soon incorporated the ability to run Java applets within web pages, and Java quickly became popular.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] The Java 1.0 compiler was re-written in Java by Arthur van Hoff to comply strictly with the Java 1.0 language specification.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] With the advent of Java 2 (released initially as J2SE 1.2 in December 1998 – 1999), new versions had multiple configurations built for different types of platforms.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] J2EE included technologies and APIs for enterprise applications typically run in server environments, while J2ME featured APIs optimized for mobile applications.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] In 2006, for marketing purposes, Sun renamed new J2 versions as *Java EE*, *Java ME*, and *Java SE*, respectively.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] In 1997, Sun Microsystems approached the ISO/IEC JTC 1 standards body and later the Ecma International to formalize Java, but it soon withdrew from the process.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Java remains a *de facto* standard, controlled through the Java Community Process.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] At one time, Sun made most of its Java implementations available without charge, despite their proprietary software status.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Sun generated revenue from Java through the selling of licenses for specialized products such as the Java Enterprise System.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] On November 13, 2006, Sun released much of its Java virtual machine (JVM) as free and open-source software (FOSS), under the terms of the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] On May 8, 2007, Sun finished the process, making all of its JVM's core code available under free software/open-source distribution terms, aside from a small portion of code to which Sun did not hold the copyright.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Sun's vice-president Rich Green said that Sun's ideal role with regard to Java was as an *evangelist*.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Following Oracle Corporation's acquisition of Sun Microsystems in 2009–10, Oracle has described itself as the steward of Java technology with a relentless commitment to fostering a community of participation and transparency.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] This did not prevent Oracle from filing a lawsuit against Google shortly after that for using Java inside the Android SDK (see the *Android* section).
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] On April 2, 2010, James Gosling resigned from Oracle.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] In January 2016, Oracle announced that Java run-time environments based on JDK 9 will discontinue the browser plugin.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Java software runs on most devices from laptops to data centers, game consoles to scientific supercomputers.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Oracle (and others) highly recommend uninstalling outdated and unsupported versions of Java, due to unresolved security issues in older versions.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] It must be architecture-neutral and portable.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] It must be interpreted, threaded, and dynamic.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] As of June 2026, Java 8, 11, 17, 21, and 25 are supported as long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Oracle released the last zero-cost public update for the legacy version Java 8 LTS in January 2019 for commercial use, although it will otherwise still support Java 8 with public updates for personal use indefinitely.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Other vendors such as Adoptium continue to offer free builds of OpenJDK's long-term support (LTS) versions.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] These builds may include additional security patches and bug fixes.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Sun has defined and supports four editions of Java targeting different application environments and segmented many of its APIs so that they belong to one of the platforms.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] The classes in the Java APIs are organized into separate groups called packages.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Each package contains a set of related interfaces, classes, subpackages and exceptions.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Sun also provided an edition called Personal Java that has been superseded by later, standards-based Java ME configuration-profile pairings.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] One design goal of Java is portability, which means that programs written for the Java platform must run similarly on any combination of hardware and operating system with adequate run time support.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] This is achieved by compiling the Java language code to an intermediate representation called JVM bytecode, instead of directly to architecture-specific machine code.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] JVM bytecode instructions are analogous to machine code, but they are intended to be executed by a virtual machine (VM) written specifically for the host hardware.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] End-users commonly use a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) installed on their device for standalone Java applications or a web browser for Java applets.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Standard libraries provide a generic way to access host-specific features such as graphics, threading, and networking.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] The use of universal bytecode makes porting simple.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] However, the overhead of interpreting bytecode into machine instructions made interpreted programs almost always run more slowly than native executables.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Just-in-time (JIT) compilers that compile byte-codes to machine code during runtime were introduced from an early stage.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Java's Hotspot compiler is actually two compilers in one, with GraalVM (included in e.g.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Java 11, but removed as of Java 16) allowing tiered compilation.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Java itself is platform-independent and is adapted to the particular platform it is to run on by a Java virtual machine (JVM), which translates the JVM bytecode into the platform's machine language.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Programs written in Java have a reputation for being slower and requiring more memory than those written in C++.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] With Java 1.5, the performance was improved with the addition of the `java.util.concurrent` package, including lock-free implementations of the ConcurrentMaps and other multi-core collections, and it was improved further with Java 1.6.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Something similar to a memory leak may still occur if a programmer's code holds a reference to an object that is no longer needed, typically when objects that are no longer needed are stored in containers that are still in use.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] If methods for a non-existent object are called, a null pointer exception is thrown.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] One of the ideas behind Java's automatic memory management model is that programmers can be spared the burden of having to perform manual memory management.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] In some languages, memory for the creation of objects is implicitly allocated on the stack or explicitly allocated and deallocated from the heap.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] In the latter case, the responsibility of managing memory resides with the programmer.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] If the program does not deallocate an object, a memory leak occurs.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] If the program attempts to access or deallocate memory that has already been deallocated, the result is undefined and difficult to predict, and the program is likely to become unstable or crash.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] This can be partially remedied by the use of smart pointers, but these add overhead and complexity.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Garbage collection does not prevent logical memory leaks, i.e. those where the memory is still referenced but never used.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Garbage collection may happen at any time.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Ideally, it will occur when a program is idle.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] It is guaranteed to be triggered if there is insufficient free memory on the heap to allocate a new object; this can cause a program to stall momentarily.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Explicit memory management is not possible in Java, however it is possible to make the JVM do garbage collection manually.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Java does not support C/C++ style pointer arithmetic, where object addresses can be arithmetically manipulated (e.g. by adding or subtracting an offset).
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] This allows the garbage collector to relocate referenced objects and ensures type safety and security.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] As in C++ and some other object-oriented languages, variables of Java's primitive data types are either stored directly in fields (for objects) or on the stack (for methods) rather than on the heap, as is commonly true for non-primitive data types (but see escape analysis).
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] This was a conscious decision by Java's designers for performance reasons.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Java contains multiple types of garbage collectors.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Since Java 9, HotSpot uses the Garbage First Garbage Collector (G1GC) as the default.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] However, there are also several other garbage collectors that can be used to manage the heap, such as the Z Garbage Collector (ZGC) introduced in Java 11, and Shenandoah GC, introduced in Java 12 but unavailable in Oracle-produced OpenJDK builds.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] Shenandoah is instead available in third-party builds of OpenJDK, such as Eclipse Temurin.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] For most applications in Java, G1GC is sufficient.
[src:dropwizard-java/java-programming-language] In prior versions of Java, such as Java 8, the Parallel Garbage Collector was used as the default garbage collector.
